		By: Eva		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.vercel.app/lewins-equation#comment-11405</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Eva]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 11 Sep 2014 04:43:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=6140#comment-11405</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Super helpful to think about in the way you frame it, James.  As a social worker, it is rather ironic, since Lewin&#039;s equation is essentially social work in practice (considering a person in their environment), which is different from other helping professional perspectives.

If a person&#039;s environment is not optimal for a person&#039;s functioning, then it doesn&#039;t support their well-being or functioning.  Programs for very vulnerable people, such as &quot;wrap around services&quot; look to change certain aspects of the environment to &quot;wrap around&quot; the needs of the vulnerable individual or family.  This equation takes it down to the most fundamental, most concrete aspects of environment and suggests how change happens and what it is that we actually have control over even when an environment is far from optimal.

Thank you!]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Super helpful to think about in the way you frame it, James.  As a social worker, it is rather ironic, since Lewin&#8217;s equation is essentially social work in practice (considering a person in their environment), which is different from other helping professional perspectives.</p>
<p>If a person&#8217;s environment is not optimal for a person&#8217;s functioning, then it doesn&#8217;t support their well-being or functioning.  Programs for very vulnerable people, such as &#8220;wrap around services&#8221; look to change certain aspects of the environment to &#8220;wrap around&#8221; the needs of the vulnerable individual or family.  This equation takes it down to the most fundamental, most concrete aspects of environment and suggests how change happens and what it is that we actually have control over even when an environment is far from optimal.</p>
<p>Thank you!</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
